nshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Cossington, Leicestershire, England":"Cossington, Leicestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Syston, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Syston, Leicestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1460–20 Mar 1530":"1460–20 March 1530","1460–1530":"1460–1530","1462–1490":"1462–1490","1479–Male":"1479–Deceased","1480–1509":"1480–1509","1485–1554":"1485–1554","1430–1464":"1430–1464","1434–1464":"1434–1464","1484":"1484","1462":"1462","1460":"1460","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","1459":"1459","1479":"1479","14 May 1485":"14 May 1485","20 Mar 1530":"20 March 1530","1434":"1434","1554":"1554","1464":"1464","1530":"1530","1430":"1430","1485":"1485","1509":"1509","Syston, Leicestershire, England":"Syston, Leicestershire, England","England":"England","Yarmouth, Norfolk, England":"Great Yarmouth, Norfolk, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Cossington, Leicestershire, England":"Cossington, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","Syston, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Syston, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Webster","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: occupational name for a weaver, from Middle English <i>webbester</i> ‘weaver’ (Old English <i>webbestre</i> ‘female weaver’). By the time of surname formation, the gender distinction of the <i>-stre</i> suffix had almost completely disappeared. Compare   Webb  ,   Webber  , and   Weaver  .","History: The name Webster was brought to North America from England independently by several different bearers in the 17th and 18th centuries. One John Webster settled in Ipswich, MA, in 1635; another John Webster (died 1661), ancestor of the lexicographer Noah Webster, emigrated to Cambridge, MA, <i>c.</i> 1631 and later became one of the founders of the colony of CT, of which he was appointed governor in 1656. Daniel Webster (1782–1852), politician and orator, was born in Salisbury, NH, a descendant of Thomas Webster, a prominent 17th-century citizen of Ipswich, MA, whose family had settled there around 1635, while he was still a child."],"variants":[{"name":"Webb","meanings":["English: occupational name for a weaver, from early Middle English <i>webbe</i> (Old English <i>webba</i> (masculine) or <i>webbe</i> (feminine), probably used of both male and female weavers). This word survived into Middle English long enough to give rise to the surname, but was already obsolescent as an agent noun; hence the secondary forms with the agent suffixes <i>-er</i> and <i>-ster</i> (see   Webster  ,   Webber   and compare   Weaver  ).","Americanized form of various like-sounding Jewish (Ashkenazic) surnames, cognates of 1, including   Weber   and <b>Weberman</b>.","History: Richard Webb, a Lowland Scot, was an admitted freeman of Boston in 1632, and in 1635 was one of the first settlers of Hartford, CT."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Webster Sr. was born in 1460, in Syston, Leicestershire, England, his father, John Webster II, was 30 and his mother, Elizabeth Leiffen, was 26. He married Agnes Bradborne in 1484, in Cossington, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom. In 1509, at the age of 49, his occupation is listed as butcher in Syston, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom. He died on 20 March 1530, in Cossington, Leicestershire, England, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1460–20 Mar 1530":"1460–20. märts 1530","1460–1530":"1460–1530","1462–1490":"1462–1490","1479–Male":"1479–Surnud","1480–1509":"1480–1509","1485–1554":"1485–1554","1430–1464":"1430–1464","1434–1464":"1434–1464","1484":"1484","1462":"1462","1460":"1460","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","1459":"1459","1479":"1479","14 May 1485":"14. mai 1485","20 Mar 1530":"20. märts 1530","1434":"1434","1554":"1554","1464":"1464","1530":"1530","1430":"1430","1485":"1485","1509":"1509","Syston, Leicestershire, England":"Syston, Leicestershire, England","England":"England","Yarmouth, Norfolk, England":"Great Yarmouth, Norfolk, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Cossington, Leicestershire, England":"Cossington, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Syston, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Syston, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1460–20 Mar 1530":"1460–20. maaliskuuta 1530","1460–1530":"1460–1530","1462–1490":"1462–1490","1479–Male":"1479–Kuollut","1480–1509":"1480–1509","1485–1554":"1485–1554","1430–1464":"1430–1464","1434–1464":"1434–1464","1484":"1484","1462":"1462","1460":"1460","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","1459":"1459","1479":"1479","14 May 1485":"14. toukokuuta 1485","20 Mar 1530":"20. maaliskuuta 1530","1434":"1434","1554":"1554","1464":"1464","1530":"1530","1430":"1430","1485":"1485","1509":"1509","Syston, Leicestershire, England":"Syston, Leicestershire, England","England":"England","Yarmouth, Norfolk, England":"Great Yarmouth, Norfolk, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Cossington, Leicestershire, England":"Cossington, Leicestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Syston, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Syston, Leicestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"